Source: Mr Surveyor Thomson
Author: HALL-JONES
Vol / Page: 45
Edition:
Quote: .. the bearers stumbled in the crab-holes on either side, or over the tussocks.
Notes: (Griffiths Collection) c1850s in 1971 Hall-Jones Mr Surveyor Thomson 45

Date: 0/0/1856
Source: Diary
Author: W.H.S. ROBERTS
Vol / Page:
Edition:
Quote: We went down a spur for two miles that was very soft from the late rain, and full of waterholes, called crab-holes. These holes were formed by the large snowgrass tussocks being burnt out roots and all, leaving a hole, or by the uprooting of trees, where the hole was very large ... In some places these holes made by(?) cattle mustering a most hazardous undertaking. In Mr Alex Garvie's report in 1858 he refers to `podge holes,' presumably a variety of `crab-holes.'
Notes: 1856 W.H.S. Roberts Diary in 1947 Beattie Early Runholding 323

Date: 0/0/1867
Source: Rambles with a Philosopher
Author: THOMPSON
Vol / Page: 22
Edition:
Quote: We had to hold by the lower spurs of the ranges, now ascending one to head the small streamlets or creeks, and then descending another; now floundering in a swamp, then stumbling into crab-holes.
Notes:

